{"title_page": "Claire E. Sterk", "text_new": "{{short description|Dutch scientist}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = \n| name = Claire E. Sterk\n| caption = \n| order = 20th\n| title = [[University President|President]] of [[Emory University]]\n| term_start = 2016\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[James W. Wagner]]\n| successor = \n| birth_name = Claire Elizabeth Sterk\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1957}}\n| birth_place = [[Netherlands]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[Erasmus University]] {{small|([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}<br>[[University of Utrecht]] {{small|([[Doctorandus|DRS]])}}\n| residence = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| profession = [[Academic administration|Academic administrator]]\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| website = http://president.emory.edu/\n}}\n'''Claire Elizabeth Sterk'''  is a Dutch scientist and the President of [[Emory University]].<ref name=Sterk_emory>{{cite web |title= Claire E. Sterk, University Provost and Executive Vice President of Academic Affairs |publisher= Emory University |url= http://president.emory.edu/university_leadership/cabinet/csterk.html |accessdate= 4 June 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160527034153/http://president.emory.edu/university_leadership/cabinet/csterk.html |archive-date= 27 May 2016 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Sterk holds faculty positions in anthropology, sociology, and women's, gender, and sexuality studies at Emory.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Research ==\nSterk has been Charles Howard Candler Professor of Public Health at Emory since 2000. Sterk is a leading figure in both [[public health]] and [[anthropology]] studying addiction, mental health, and [[HIV/AIDS]]. She was the first person to identify the risk of HIV infection due to unprotected sex among crack cocaine users.\n\nSterk received a PhD in [[sociology]] from [[Erasmus University]] in [[Rotterdam]] and her doctorandus degree in medical anthropology from the University of Utrecht.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.emory.edu/stories/2016/06/sterk_new_emory_president/campus.html|title=Internationally acclaimed public health researcher and academic leader Claire E. Sterk named Emory University's next president|date=2016-06-03|website=news.emory.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-21}}</ref> Her undergraduate degree is from the Free University in Amsterdam.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nSterk is the author of two books\u2014''Fast Lives: Women Who Use Crack Cocaine'' and ''Tricking and Tripping: Prostitution in the Era of AIDS''.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=ntt_athr_dp_sr_1?_encoding=UTF8&field-author=Claire%20Sterk&search-alias=books&sort=relevancerank Books : \"Claire Sterk\"], at Amazon</ref> She has since written another book.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.gs.emory.edu/vulnerability/faculty/bios/sterk-claire.html|title=Claire E. Sterk, PhD {{!}} Emory University {{!}} Atlanta GA|website=web.gs.emory.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-21}}</ref> She has also published more than 100 articles and book chapters.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe became President of Emory on September 1, 2016.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://whsc.emory.edu/about/leadership/bios/sterk-claire.html|title=Claire E. Sterk|website=whsc.emory.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-21}}</ref> Prior to that time, she had served as provost and executive vice president for academic affairs.<ref name=\":2\" /> She held the position of president in the Alcohol, Drug, and Tobacco section of the American Sociological Association.<ref name=\":0\" /> Sterk is the principal investigator of Building Interdisciplinary Research Careers in Women's Health, which is funded by the Eunice Kennedy Shriver National Institute of Child Health and Human Development.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn November 13, 2019, Sterk announced that she would resign as Emory president at the end of the 2019-2020 school year and return to teaching in the Rollins School of Public Health.\n\nSterk speaks four languages.<ref name=\":1\" />\n==Honors and awards==\nShe was elected to the [[National Academy of Medicine]] in 2018  <ref>{{cite web |title=National Academy of Medicine Elects 85 New Members |url=https://nam.edu/national-academy-of-medicine-elects-85-new-members/ |website=National Academy of Medicine |accessdate=2 May 2019 |date=15 October 2018}}</ref> and elected as a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://members.amacad.org/content/members/newFellows.aspx|title=2019 Fellows and International Honorary Members with their affiliations at the time of election |website=members.amacad.org|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302174101/https://members.amacad.org/content/members/newFellows.aspx|archive-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160607131258/http://www.cfar.emory.edu/bio/investigator/sterk.html Emory University, Center for AIDS Research Clair E. Sterk bio]\n\n{{Emory University presidents}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sterk, Claire E.}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch sociologists]]\n[[Category:Dutch anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Women sociologists]]\n[[Category:Women anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Medical anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Emory University people]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS researchers]]\n[[Category:Dutch women scientists]]\n[[Category:Erasmus University Rotterdam alumni]]\n[[Category:Utrecht University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Kerkrade]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Emory University]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women heads of universities and colleges]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dutch scientist}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = \n| name = Claire E. Sterk\n| caption = \n| order = 20th\n| title = [[University President|President]] of [[Emory University]]\n| t